{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_glasgow_ver01/data/sn84036106/0051717886A/1949060201/1232.xml":{"full_text":"Page 4\nstigtwiaxsPast\nMXUABD 'WUaUNK,\nBAttor-iand Mt\u00dfirt l J\nRATIONAL EDITORIAL\nEntered as second class matter on\nJune 22. 1946, at the U. S. Post\nOffice at St. I matins. Montana,\nunder the Act of March 3, 1879.\nPublished even\u2019 Thursday at St.\nIgnatius, Lake County* Mont. The\ntown ;s located in a very beautiful,\nfertile and historical spot of the\nlower Flathead valley locally\nknown as \u201cThe Mission\u201d and the\nMission valley.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES: $3.00 per\nyear in advance in Lake county:\noutside of Lake countv (except\nDixon) $3.50. Six months $1.75.\nADVERTISING RATES:\nAny 1-time display advertise\nment, 40c per column inch; steady\nlocal advertisers. 35c per column\nInch; \u201cstanding\u201d advertisements\n(at least* four insertions with no\nchange whatever) 30c per column\n\u2019lnch: outside advertising (foreign),\n42 cents per column inch; political\nadvertisements, 45c per column\nInch: legal advertising at statutory\nrates. ,r v 7ri\nWant ads. readet. ads, notices,\n12c per Hne for first insertion, 6c\nper line for each subsequent in\nsertion. Cards of Thanks; tl.oo.\nENTERTAINED FACULTY\nMrs. John Ross Mf?-. Ma x\nStark entertained at 5 a luncheon\nat the home of T \u2019Stark on\nThursday afternoon of last week\nin honor of all faculty members of\nThe Lower Flathead Parish of th*\nMethodist Church\nArlee \u2014Church Services' at 10\na m.; Sunday School at 11.\nSt. Ignatius\u2014Church Services at\n11:15 a. m.: Sunday School at 10.\nDixon\u2014Church Services at 8:00\np, m.. Sunday School at 10 a. m.\nRev. Paul W. Ivbs. Pastor\n000\nCatholic Church\nMasses at 8:00 a. m. and 10 a. m.\non Sundays; weekdays at 6:30 a. m.\n000\nZion Lutheran Church\nSunday School at 7:00 p. m.\nChurch Services at 8:00 p. m.\nYou are invited.\nTIME TABLES\nN. P. R. R., RAVALLI\nWest Bound No. 1 4:23 p.m.\n(Does not stop)\nWest Bound No. 3 1:00 p.m.\nEast Bound No. 2.\u2014 2:19 p. m\n(Does not stop)\nEast Bound No. 4 5:29 a. m.\nN. P. TRANSPORT, St. Ignatius\nSouth Bound bus 11:55 a. m.\nNorth Bound bus 4:30 p..m.\nINTERMOUNTAIN BUB, St. Ign.\nSOUTH BOUND: _ 9:15 \u00ab.m.\n2:01 p. m.\n7^l\u2019 fem.\nNORTH BOUND U:26S. n.\n4:45 p. m.\n\nMISSION VALLpY LOCAL\nNO. 48, Farmers Union\nMeets Ist Friday of each month\nat Equity Hall, St. Ignatius\nR. H. Anderson President\nMrs. I. Rognrud i Secy.-Treas.\nMISSION GRANGE NO. 105\nMeets Ist and 3rd Thursdays of\neach month at Equity Hall.\nEd. Linderman Master\nAlma Sipe Secretary\njames r. w. McCarthy\nPOST NO. 106\nMeets the\n2nd Thurs\nday of each\nmonth. Vis\niting Le g\nionnaires\nwelcome.\nVirgil Phillips _ Commander\nVictor CordiOL Jr, ^.-.-Adjutant\nFLATHEAD LODGE NO. 112\na.f. a xlt v\nft '\"Meetf the 2nd and 4th\n_ JJbtj Tuesdays of saeh Me.\n1 aiwaH woleomo.\nWalter CordW.i.\u2019.\u2019.'WlirsiUpfariHiter\nW. G. Moontjoy SewMery\nr-\u2019 -we --y t\nfWIWWw\nAdm||ted\nMrs. Clara Burke, Mrs. Russell\nThorrfock Daniel and Bonnie Hill\nci re, Maureen Swaney, Mrs. Wm.\nPolson, Mrs. Jack Morigeau, Dave\nHanson, Mrs. ^Walter Freshour and\nbaby girl, Mrs. Frank Tyro and ba\nby boy. Henry Nicholas, Mrs. Moses\nAuld. Mrs. Chris Pederson, Mrs.\nMatthew Steele, Mrs. Crandall\nPaulson and baby girl, Ruth Cordis\nMrs. Oscar Luddington, Esther\nLozeau, Mrs. Robert Gilchrist and\nbaby boy, Mrs. Earl Atchley, Frank\nBellmore, Rudy J. Stoll, Mrs. Phi 1\n\u0964ip Crawford. Dorothy Erickson,\nMrs. Adrian Raminez, Donald Pet-\nI tit, Mrs. Phillip Kuntz, Judith A\n-1 bell, Seraphine Lefthand. Louise\nStasso, Mrs. Caroline Broe.\nDischarged\nHenry Nicholas, Mrs. Charles\u2022\nGardipe. Mrs. Frank Layton, Mrs.\nRussell Thornock, Mis. Richadj\nLensman, Daniel and Bonnie Hill-i\naire. Maureen Swaney, Mrs. Wal-!\nter Starkel and baby boy, Mrs.\nRobert Strong and baby boy, Da* e\nHansen, Mrs. Chris Pederson, Mrs.\nPatrick Airhart and baby girl. Mrs.\nMoses Auld, Mrs. Crandall Paulson\nand baby girl, Mrs. Hairiet Engh*.\nRuth Cordis, Daniel Barber, Janis\nSullivan, Mrs. Earl Atchley, Rudy\nJ. Stoll, Andrew Woodcock, Mrs.\nBertie Beherndt. Dorothy Erickson\nMrs. Adrian Raminez, Jess Cou\nture, Mrs Frank .Gray, Mrs. R.\nBrowning.\nN. M. STACY INVESTIGATING\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK AT ARCO\nNorman Stacy left on Tuesday\nfor Arco, Idaho, to investigate the\npossibilities of opening a business\nthere, which promises to be a\nboom town if the government\u2019s\natomic energy plant goes into op\neration there.\nMr. Stacy said that he opened\nhis plumbing and electric shop in\nSt. Ignatius in anticipation that a\n'CHURCH OF JESUS CHRIST OF\nLATTER DAY SAINTS\n(Sunday)\nOfficers Meeting 9:45 a. m.\nSunday School 10:00 a. m.\nSacrament Meeting 11:30 a. m.\nPriesthood Meeting 7:30 p. rr\u00bb.\nFireside Meeting 8:45 p. m.\nTuesday\nRelief Society 2:00 p. m.\nI Primary 4:00 p. m.\nMutual 8:00 p. m\nillillllllllilllllllllllllllllllllllllllllllllll*lllllllllllllllllllllll\nWANT ADS\nRATE: 12c per line for Ist in\nsertion: 6c per line for each ad\nditional insertion.\nilliiimiiiitiiiiili|iiiiiiillliiiilliiliilliiiiiiiM>iiiiuJiiiimii I\nLOST Licens plate no. 15 2044\nW. J. Smyth, St. Ignatius. 49-1 tp\nWANTED\u2014IOO radios to repair!\nGot one? Call Mission Electric,\nSt. Ignatius. 43-tfc\nFOR SALE\u20143 lots in St. Ignatius,\neach 50x150 feet, choice loca\ntion. Write or see George San\ndon, St. Ignatius, Mont. 48-3tp\nFOR SALE \u2014Gravel, sand and mill\nwood. See George Marks or call\n6-F-17, St. Ignatius. 51-tfc\nFOR SALE\u2014AII new, thoroughly\nbuilt modern 4-room house, nice\nlocation, 220-volt wiring full in\nsulation, reasonable for cash, or\nterms to reliable party. For\nfurther information, see Mrs.\nPat Lentz, phone 47-W-3. St.\nIgnatius. 48-2tp\nFOR SALE Jdhn Deere hay\nchopper and side delivery rake\nused one yenr; also one wagon. I\ntwo boxes. See S. P. Beaver or\nMax Stark, St. Ignatius. 48-3tc\nFOR SALE\u2014Cheap, davennort and\nchair. Ray Stoll, St. Ignatius,\nMont. 48-2tc\nFOR SALE\u2014I 947 Ford Tudoor. ex\ncellent condition, low mileage.\nCan be financed with one-third\ndown. Radio, heater, spot. Mis\nsion Realty. 48-2tc\nFOR RENT\u2014Good 28-acre pasture,\nplenty of shade, water, etc.\nSteve Peone, Post Creek. 48-2tc\nFOR SALE\u2014Battery fed broilers,\ntender, well flavored, any num\nber. any time. Also some N. H.\nRed pullets from 6 to 13 weeks\nold. Al Meyers, St. Ignatius,\nMont. 48-tfc\nFOR SALE \u2014Moiese sand and grav\nel. Delivered anywhere. Phone\nBF-33, Charlo, or write Jensen\nHowell, Moiese, Mont. 44-tfc\nWANTED Refrigerators to re\npair, all makes, prompt service.\nCall Mission Etoctric, St. Igna\ntius. 43-tfc.\n194 ft 2-doer Chev\nrolet sedan; Coronado separator;\npower take off pulley, 3-phase\nelectric motor; 2 milk cows,\nrake, Mine detector, feed grind\ner. belt, hot water tank, porch\nswing, pair of snow shoes. Mrs.l\nGeorie Ruckhouse, St. Ignatius.^\nShop in St. Ignatius I\nWWMNB mr\nsewer system weblid be Construct\ned... Now that the council has de\ncided'to wait a year or so\" \u201cbefore\ntaking the matter up again, Mr.\nStacy is of the opinion that the\nbusiness outlook in his line will\nnot warrant him maintaining his\nshop and stock of plumbing and\nelectrical supplies.\nI If things at Arco \u201cdon\u2019t look too\ngood,\u201d Mr. Stacy said that he will\nvery likely continue in the real\nestate and insurance business in\nSt. Ignatius.\nCARD OF THANKS\n1 The Garden Wall wishes to thank\neveryone who so generously contri\nbuted their time, food, flowers\nand money to help make our Mem\norial Day dinner a success. We es\n[peciaily wish to thank the Purity\n[Bakery, The American Legion, the\n\u0964Art Class of the high school and\nthe Foothills club for the services\n[they rendered to us. Also those\nwho patronized our dinner and\nsale of flowers. We hope you will\n[continue to help us make this an-j\n>nual affair a success and look for-|\nward to seeing you there next\nyear.\nLydia Hammond.\ni Garden Wall Club Pres.\nPOLSON MEN CALLERS; ONE\nIS DEALER FOR NEW MARV AIR\nHEATING-COOLING DEVICE\nVisitors in St. Ignatius Tuesday\nfrom the county seat included Ken\nChatwood and Walter P. Williams.\nMr. Chatwood formerly operated\ni the Montana Junior shop at Polson\nand is now erecting a tourist camp\n,on the East Lake Shore road. Mr.\nWilliams is the owner of a ref ri g-\neration service at Polson and is\nthe dealer for the new Marvair\nheating and cooling system. Read\nthe ad about Marvair in this issue.\nIt is claimed that Marvair requires\n.no fuel and no attention winter\nor summer. It is said tp heat with-\ni out combustion, eliminating rire\nand explosion hazards, soot and\nashes. In winter, heat is derived\nfrom the earth and in summer,\nheat is dissipated into the earth.\nJUNE MAY BE WETTISH\nAs The POST goes to press to\nday, rainfall is continuing. Looks\nlike a \u201csoaker\u201d plus.\ni LETTER Buck!\n\ni Follow The Crowd\nTO POLSON\nSaturday and Sunday June 4 and 5\nEIGHTH ANNUAL I\nI Polson Rodeo\nI 7 MAJOR EVENTS 7 TRADE EXPANSION I\nSaddle Brone Riding AWARDS TO BE GIVEN I\nI Bareback AWAY EREE! I\nI Brahma Bull Riding J\nWild Horse Race\u2014l Mile Electric Stove\nBulldogging Deluxe Refrigerator\nWild Cow Milking _,\nCalf Roping Home Freezer J\nJ PLCS Boys\u2019 and Girls\u2019 Bicycles\nBullfighting and Clowning And Many Other Fine Gifts\nJ Rodeo Stock Furnished by Jake Johnson. Penna. Mont.\nI Big Night\u2019Revue Star-Studded I\nI Stupendous I\nJUNE 4 I\n--MISSION DRUG--\nK. H. HURT, Proprietor\nST. IGNATIUS MONTANA\nil\nPrescriptions by Registered Pharmacist\nToiletries, Confections, Tobaccos, Cards\nExtensive Line of Gift Goods, the best\nUp-to-date Fountain Service, Magasines\nWAV W BCIFTfAYIOWWAB 2.02\nINCHES; LEM THAN HALF OP\nMAY A YEAR AGO\nThe U. S. weather report for\nthis area, as prepared by the Flat\nhead Indian Irrigation project\u2019s\nheadquarters in St. Ignatius, shows\nthat the precipation during the\nmonth of May was 2.02 inches, and\nthat amount is .06 of an inch be-\nI low the 41 year mean.\nBy way of conti ast, the weather\n1 report shows that the precipita\nfor May a year ago was 444 in\nches. or the third wettest May\nin 41 years on the project.\nThe highest temperature for the\n'month was 89. and thel oewst, 29.\nThe mean temperature for the\nI month was 57.4 degrees, which was\n4.2 degrees above the 41-year\nI mean.\nMRS. PAUL DIES TODAY:\nLEAVES MANY DECENDANTS\nI Mrs. Mary Mox-Mox Paul, 76,\npassed away ths Thursday morn\ni ing at the local hospital after a\nlingering illness. She was born at\n1 Kama h, Idaho and has been a res\n-1 ident on the Flathead reservation.\nBesides her husband, Louie Paul. 1\nI she is survived by four daughters,\nMrs. Albert Taylor and Mrs. Chris\ntine Red-Elk both of Lapwai. Ida\ni ho, Mrs. James Green of Spauld-\nI ing, Idaho and Miss Florence Paul\nof St. Ignatius. She is also survived\nby two sons, Art J. McConnville of\nOrovino, Idaho and Joe George of\nToppenish, Washington. Also there\nare 21 great grand children and\nI 18 grand children. Remains will be\nI removed to from the Fearon Chap\nel to the Baptiste Hewankorn\nat Arlee and Saturday noon the\ni body will be shipped to LewisCcm.\nFuneral services will be held n\n1 Monday morning at Kamiah, Idaho\nand interment in the family plot\nthere.\nSTATE VETERAN WELFARE\nWORKER NOT TO CALL\nAGAIN UNTIL JULY 1\nThe Missoula office of the Vet\nerans Welfare Commission, which\nhas for some time been sending\na representative here on the first\nand third week of each month, has\n'announced that due to the short\nage of funds for the remainder of\nthe fiscal year' ending Jahe* 30?\n1949 the local office wfl! be ufiable\nto carry on this Itinerary service\nMay 15th to July 1, 1949. This ser-,\nwill again be re-established Julyl.\nCITATION AND ORDER TO\nSHOW CAUSE\nIn the District Court of the Fourth\nJudicial District of the State of\nMontana, in and for the County\nof Lake.\nIN THE MATTER OF THE ADOP\nTION OF JAMES MORLEY\nGRIGGS. A MINOR.\nTHE STATE OF MONTANA TO:\nMORLEY JAMES GRIGGS, RES\nPONDENT, GREETING:\nYou are hereby cited to be and\nappear before the above entitled\nCourt, at and in the City of Polson,\nLake County Montana, on the 19th\ni day of Juiy, 1949, at lU:00 o\u2019clock\na. m. of said day. at the Court\nRoom thereof in said City,\nCounty and State aforesaid, then\nand there to show cause, if any\nyou have, why the petition for a\ndoption of James Morley Griggs, a\nj minor, filed in this Court by Way\n'ne Woolley and Norma Woolley,\nthe petitioners, should not oe\ngranted, and an Order\u2019 of this\nj Court made authorizing said adop\ntion in the manner and form as by\nlaw provided.\nWitness, the Honorable Albert\nBesancon, Judge of said District\nCourt, and the seal of said Court\naffixed this 24th day of May, 1949.\n(Court Seal) JAMES HARBERT.\nClerk of said District\nCourt, Polson, Lake County,\n1 Montana.\nBy Mabel E. Violette, Deputy\nF. N. Hamman, Polson, Montana,\nAttorney for the Petitioners.\n(4 Pubs. June 2,9, 16, 23.)\nBoost for St. Ignatius. It pays!\nj MUSICAL NOTE\n3 RECORD SHOP f\n\n1 614 S. Higgins Ave. J\n1 r\n2 Missoula. Montana\nI\nINEW and USED RECORDS;\n3 j\n3 Mail Orders Accepted I\nI\n3 Opne until 8 I\u2019. M.\n3\nON FRIDAYS j\na I\nnr-nf-'nnnnr-mr-nnnnnnnnnnnnf\nNEW BUS SCHEDUT.E\nMAKES FINE CONNECTION\nWITH \u201cNORTH COAST\u201d\nThe Northern Pacific Transport\nbus now leaves Polson at 11 a. m.\ndaily, except Sunday, instead of\n9:10 a. m^ and arrives Missoula\n1:05 p. m., shortening the sched\nule 25 minutes and making con\nvenient connections with the\nstreamlined North Coast Limited,\nI both east and west. The bus leaves\nRonan 11:25 a. m., St. Ignatius\n11:55 a. m.. Ravalli 12:05 p. m.\nand Arlee 12:20 p. m. I^ater ar\nrival at Ravalli provides conven\nient connections with westbound\nN. P. Train No. 3.\nNorthbound, the Transport bus\nleaves Missoula 3:15 p. m. daily, ex\ncept Sunday, 25 minutes earlier\nthan before. Leaves Arlee 4 p. m.,\nRavalli 4:20 p. m., St. Ignatius\n4:30 p. m., Ronan 4:55 p. m. and\narrives In Polson 5:20 p. m.\nNOTE On Sundays, when ihe\nTransport buses do not operate on\nthe Missoula-Polson run, Transport\nCo. tickets will be honored on In\ntermountain Transportation Co. 4\nbuses. \u2014G. W. Smith, Agent,\nNorthern Pacific Railway, Ravalli.\n(Adv. May 26, June 2 9)\nARLEE GARAGE\nJohn A. Morigeau, Prop.\nGas, Oil, Repairing, Welding\nTires and Auto Accessories\nMrs. Marcie Gill. Corsetier\nChans Foundation Garments,\nBrassiers Made to Measure.\nSold on 30-day Guarantee.\nBox 844 St. Ignatius\nCARPENTER WORK\nEither by Contract or Hour\nFREE ESTIMATES\nELMER ROSE, 1 Mile W. of\nLeon Club House\nALFRED FREY.. Sr.\nRLILDERS HARDWARE\nPlumbing, Sporting Goods r\nST. IGNATIUS MONT.\n\u25a0nrtJfeiMY, June \u2018tins\nB -Mir Mt\nPEDER PEDERSEN\nLicensed and Bonded\nReal Estate Broker\nList your property today and\nget ready to move away.\nRONAN MONT.\nF. N. HAMMAN\nLAWYER\nPractice in State and Federal\nCourts; Probate Matters\nPOLSON MONT.\nIL 11. W 1 E D M A N\nLAWYER\nPolson Montana\nMARK H. DERR\nATTORNEY AT LAW\nOity Attorney for St. Ignatius\nOffice at\nPOLSON MONTANA\nSTANLEY M. DOYLE\nATTORNEY-AT-LAW\nGeneral Law Practice\n(Over Security Bank Bldg.)\nPOLSON MONTANA\nDR. F W. HAIGHT\nCHIROPRACTOR at POLSON\nPhones: Office 126, Rea. 7K\nHours: 10 to 12; 2 to 5. Even\nings 7 to 8, Tues. Fri.\nFoot troubles corrected, Colon\ndisorders scientifically treated,\nX-Ray picturee taken\nFEARON\nCHAPEL\n\u201cHome for Funerals\u201d\nEFFICIENT\nDEPENDABLE\nRELIABLE\n\nAMBULANCE\nFLOWERS, ALL OCCASIONS\nMONUMENTS\n\nr PHONE 37-W-2\nST. IGNATIUS MONT.\nSLLIER SHOE\nSERVICE\nInvites Comparison with\nOther Shops\nFOR PRICE anti QUALITY\nof WORKMANSHIP\nLaces, Polishes, Heel Plates\nWHILE-U WAIT JOBS\nKNOPP\nWELDING A ITXIT SHOP\nWelding of all types any place\nGlen Knopp, Proprietor\nST. IGNATIUS. MONTANA\nWESTERN LIFE\